comments.body:
@n1hility I am not running a VPN and I tried running after disabling firewall, still the same issue. I think the issue is with the Fedora WSL that podman creates and uses.

I isolated this by installing a new Oracle Linux distro and installed podman inside this Linux env and was able to pull and run images. 
Also a side question is there a way I can use this oracle linux distro to work with podman that I have installed on windows? I looked at the podman machine commands but didn't find one that would help me use this.

@n1hility I think I figured out the issue. The WSL distros have the nameserver wrong so we would need to edit it. After editing the distro has external network access established, I validated by doing a curl from within the linux distro. 
Next I did `wsl -d podman-machine-default curl google.com` on another CLI even when the earlier CLI was open the changes of the nameserver was overwritten automatically to the host machine's IP.

I could resolve it by installing chattr using the command `dnf install e2fsprogs` for fedora and making the `/etc/resolv.conf` immutable  by using the command `sudo chattr +i /etc/resolv.conf` after editing the nameserver. Making the file immutable is the critical step in resolving this.
